 <id>0811.3785</id><submitter>Chuanjia Shan</submitter><version version='v1'><date>Mon, 24 Nov 2008 01:04:16 GMT</date><size>7kb</size></version><version version='v2'><date>Sat, 3 Jan 2009 08:29:24 GMT</date><size>7kb</size></version><title>The controlled teleportation of an arbitrary two-atom entangled state in
  driven cavity QED</title><authors>Chuan-Jia Shan, Ji-Bing Liu, Tang-Kun Liu, Yan-Xia Huang, Hong Li</authors><categories>quant-ph</categories><comments>10 pages</comments><journal-ref>International Journal of Theoretical Physics,Published online: 31
  December 2008</journal-ref><doi>10.1007/s10773-008-9924-6</doi><license>http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/</license><abstract>  In this paper, we propose a scheme for the controlled teleportation of an
arbitrary two-atom entangled state
$|\phi&gt;_{12}=a|gg&gt;_{12}+b|ge&gt;_{12}+c|eg&gt;_{12}+d|ee&gt;_{12}$ in driven cavity QED.
An arbitrary two-atom entangled state can be teleported perfectly with the help
of the cooperation of the third side by constructing a three-atom GHZ entangled
state as the controlled channel. This scheme does not involve apparent (or
direct) Bell-state measurement and is insensitive to the cavity decay and the
thermal field. The probability of the success in our scheme is 1.0.
