 <id>0811.3907</id><submitter>Kouhei Washiyama</submitter><version version='v1'><date>Mon, 24 Nov 2008 18:17:12 GMT</date><size>39kb</size></version><title>Extraction of nucleus-nucleus potential and energy dissipation from
  dynamical mean-field theory</title><authors>Kouhei Washiyama, Denis Lacroix</authors><categories>nucl-th</categories><comments>6 pages, 5 figures. Uses aipxfm.sty. A talk given at the FUSION08:
  New Aspects of Heavy Ion Collisions Near the Coulomb Barrier, September
  22-26, 2008, Chicago, USA</comments><doi>10.1063/1.3108863</doi><license>http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/</license><abstract>  Nucleus-nucleus interaction potentials in heavy-ion fusion reactions are
extracted from the microscopic time-dependent Hartree-Fock theory. When the
center-of-mass energy is much higher than the Coulomb barrier energy, extracted
potentials identify with the frozen density approximation. As the
center-of-mass energy decreases to the Coulomb barrier energy, potentials
become energy dependent. This dependence indicates dynamical reorganization of
internal degrees of freedom and leads to a reduction of the &quot;apparent&quot; barrier.
Including this effect leads to the Coulomb barrier energy very close to
experimental one. Aspects of one-body energy dissipation extracted from the
mean-field theory are discussed.
</abstract></arXivRaw>
