 <arXivRaw xsi:schemaLocation='http://arxiv.org/OAI/arXivRaw/ http://arxiv.org/OAI/arXivRaw.xsd' xmlns='http://arxiv.org/OAI/arXivRaw/' xmlns:xsi='http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance'>
 <id>0811.3952</id><submitter>Ulrich Sperhake</submitter><version version='v1'><date>Mon, 24 Nov 2008 20:51:26 GMT</date><size>202kb</size></version><version version='v2'><date>Thu, 20 Aug 2009 02:49:59 GMT</date><size>207kb</size></version><title>Black-hole binary simulations: the mass ratio 10:1</title><authors>Jose A. Gonzalez, Ulrich Sperhake, Bernd Bruegmann</authors><categories>gr-qc</categories><comments>To match published version</comments><journal-ref>Phys.Rev.D79:124006,2009</journal-ref><doi>10.1103/PhysRevD.79.124006</doi><license>http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/</license><abstract>  We present the first numerical simulations of an initially non-spinning
black-hole binary with mass ratio as large as 10:1 in full general relativity.
The binary completes approximately 3 orbits prior to merger and radiates about
0.415% of the total energy and 12.48% of the initial angular momentum in the
form of gravitational waves. The single black hole resulting from the merger
acquires a kick of about 66.7 km/s relative to the original center of mass
frame. The resulting gravitational waveforms are used to validate existing
formulas for the recoil, final spin and radiated energy over a wider range of
the symmetric mass ratio parameter eta=M1*M2/(M1+M2)^2 than previously
possible. The contributions of l &gt; 2 multipoles are found to visibly influence
the gravitational wave signal obtained at fixed inclination angles.
</abstract></arXivRaw>
