<metadata>
 <arXivRaw xsi:schemaLocation='http://arxiv.org/OAI/arXivRaw/ http://arxiv.org/OAI/arXivRaw.xsd' xmlns='http://arxiv.org/OAI/arXivRaw/' xmlns:xsi='http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance'>
 <id>0811.3980</id><submitter>Barry Sanders</submitter><version version='v1'><date>Mon, 24 Nov 2008 21:16:06 GMT</date><size>14kb</size></version><version version='v2'><date>Mon, 19 Oct 2009 22:16:17 GMT</date><size>12kb</size></version><title>Time-reversal frameness and superselection</title><authors>Gilad Gour, Barry C. Sanders and Peter S. Turner</authors><categories>quant-ph</categories><comments>10 pp</comments><journal-ref>Journal of Mathematical Physics 50: 102105 (Oct 2009)</journal-ref><doi>10.1063/1.3243821</doi><license>http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/</license><abstract>  We show that appropriate superpositions of motional states are a reference
frame resource that enables breaking of time -reversal superselection so that
two parties lacking knowledge about the other's direction of time can still
communicate. We identify the time-reversal reference frame resource states and
determine the corresponding frameness monotone, which connects time-reversal
frameness to entanglement. In contradistinction to other studies of reference
frame quantum resources, this is the first analysis that involves an
antiunitary rather than unitary representation.
</abstract></arXivRaw>
