<record>
<header>
 <identifier>oai:arXiv.org:0811.3987</identifier>
 <datestamp>2010-01-22</datestamp>
 <setSpec>math</setSpec>
</header>
<metadata>
 <arXivRaw xsi:schemaLocation='http://arxiv.org/OAI/arXivRaw/ http://arxiv.org/OAI/arXivRaw.xsd' xmlns='http://arxiv.org/OAI/arXivRaw/' xmlns:xsi='http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance'>
 <id>0811.3987</id><submitter>Matthew Daws</submitter><version version='v1'><date>Mon, 24 Nov 2008 22:22:21 GMT</date><size>15kb</size></version><title>Preduals of semigroup algebras</title><authors>Matthew Daws, Hung Le Pham, Stuart White</authors><categories>math.FA</categories><comments>17 pages, LaTeX</comments><msc-class>43A20; 22A20</msc-class><journal-ref>Semigroup Forum, 80, 61--78, 2010.</journal-ref><license>http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/</license><abstract>  For a locally compact group $G$, the measure convolution algebra $M(G)$
carries a natural coproduct. In previous work, we showed that the canonical
predual $C_0(G)$ of $M(G)$ is the unique predual which makes both the product
and the coproduct on $M(G)$ weak$^*$-continuous. Given a discrete semigroup
$S$, the convolution algebra $\ell^1(S)$ also carries a coproduct. In this
paper we examine preduals for $\ell^1(S)$ making both the product and the
coproduct weak$^*$-continuous. Under certain conditions on $S$, we show that
$\ell^1(S)$ has a unique such predual. Such $S$ include the free semigroup on
finitely many generators. In general, however, this need not be the case even
for quite simple semigroups and we construct uncountably many such preduals on
$\ell^1(S)$ when $S$ is either $\mathbb Z_+\times\mathbb Z$ or $(\mathbb
N,\cdot)$.
</abstract></arXivRaw>
