 <arXivRaw xsi:schemaLocation='http://arxiv.org/OAI/arXivRaw/ http://arxiv.org/OAI/arXivRaw.xsd' xmlns='http://arxiv.org/OAI/arXivRaw/' xmlns:xsi='http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance'>
 <id>0811.4206</id><submitter>Chun-Yen Shen</submitter><version version='v1'><date>Wed, 26 Nov 2008 02:41:06 GMT</date><size>6kb</size></version><version version='v2'><date>Mon, 1 Dec 2008 18:56:19 GMT</date><size>6kb</size></version><version version='v3'><date>Tue, 16 Dec 2008 02:48:15 GMT</date><size>6kb</size></version><title>On the size of the set A(A+1)</title><authors>M. Z. Garaev and Chun-Yen Shen</authors><categories>math.NT</categories><comments>Minor corrections</comments><msc-class>11B75</msc-class><license>http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/</license><abstract>  Let $F_p$ be the field of a prime order $p.$ For a subset $A\subset F_p$ we
consider the product set $A(A+1).$ This set is an image of $A\times A$ under
the polynomial mapping $f(x,y)=xy+x:F_p\times F_p\to F_p.$ In the present paper
we show that if $|A|&lt;p^{1/2},$ then $$ |A(A+1)|\ge |A|^{106/105+o(1)}.$$ If
$|A|&gt;p^{2/3},$ then we prove that $$|A(A+1)|\gg \sqrt{p |A|}$$ and show that
this is the optimal in general settings bound up to the implied constant. We
also estimate the cardinality of $A(A+1)$ when $A$ is a subset of real numbers.
We show that in this case one has the Elekes type bound $$ |A(A+1)|\gg
|A|^{5/4}. $$
