<metadata>
 <arXivRaw xsi:schemaLocation='http://arxiv.org/OAI/arXivRaw/ http://arxiv.org/OAI/arXivRaw.xsd' xmlns='http://arxiv.org/OAI/arXivRaw/' xmlns:xsi='http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance'>
 <id>0811.4471</id><submitter>Guo-Zhu Liu</submitter><version version='v1'><date>Thu, 27 Nov 2008 05:32:00 GMT</date><size>55kb</size></version><version version='v2'><date>Wed, 22 Apr 2009 06:57:37 GMT</date><size>126kb</size></version><version version='v3'><date>Mon, 11 May 2009 07:59:55 GMT</date><size>126kb</size></version><title>Interaction and excitonic insulating transition in graphene</title><authors>Guo-Zhu Liu, Wei Li, and Geng Cheng</authors><categories>cond-mat.str-el cond-mat.mes-hall</categories><comments>7 pages, 4 figures, to appear in Phys. Rev. B</comments><journal-ref>Phys. Rev. B 79, 205429 (2009)</journal-ref><license>http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/</license><abstract>  The strong long-range Coulomb interaction between massless Dirac fermions in
graphene can drive a semimetal-insulator transition. We show that this
transition is strongly suppressed when the Coulomb interaction is screened by
such effects as disorder, thermal fluctuation, doping, and finite volume. It is
completely suppressed once the screening factor $\mu$ is beyond a threshold
$\mu_{c}$ even for infinitely strong coupling. However, such transition is
still possible if there is an additional strong contact four-fermion
interaction. The differences between screened and contact interactions are also
discussed.
</abstract></arXivRaw>
