<metadata>
 <arXivRaw xsi:schemaLocation='http://arxiv.org/OAI/arXivRaw/ http://arxiv.org/OAI/arXivRaw.xsd' xmlns='http://arxiv.org/OAI/arXivRaw/' xmlns:xsi='http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance'>
 <id>0811.4561</id><submitter>Josef Ashkenazi</submitter><version version='v1'><date>Thu, 27 Nov 2008 15:11:18 GMT</date><size>461kb</size></version><title>A unified theory for the cuprates, iron-based and similar
  superconducting systems: non-Fermi-liquid to Fermi-liquid crossover,
  low-energy and waterfall anomalies</title><authors>J. Ashkenazi</authors><categories>cond-mat.supr-con cond-mat.str-el</categories><comments>4 pages, 2 figues</comments><license>http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/</license><abstract>  A unified theory is outlined for the cuprates, Fe-based, and related
superconductors. Their low-energy excitations are approached in terms of
auxiliary particles representing combinations of atomic-like electron
configurations, and the introduction of a Lagrange Bose field enables their
treatment as bosons or fermions. This theory correctly describes the observed
phase diagram of the cuprates, including the non-Fermi-liquid to FL crossover
in the normal state, the existence of Fermi arcs below T^* and of &quot;marginal-FL&quot;
behavior above it. The anomalous behavior of numerous physical quantities is
accounted for, including kink- and waterfall-like spectral features, the drop
in the scattering rates below T^* and more radically below T_c, and an
effective increase in the density of carriers with T and \omega, reflected in
transport, optical and other properties. Also is explained the correspondence
between T_c, the resonance-mode energy, and the increase in the gap below T_c.
</abstract></arXivRaw>
