<metadata>
 <arXivRaw xsi:schemaLocation='http://arxiv.org/OAI/arXivRaw/ http://arxiv.org/OAI/arXivRaw.xsd' xmlns='http://arxiv.org/OAI/arXivRaw/' xmlns:xsi='http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance'>
 <id>0811.4574</id><submitter>Laurens Keek</submitter><version version='v1'><date>Thu, 27 Nov 2008 16:03:26 GMT</date><size>79kb</size></version><title>On burning regimes and long duration X-ray bursts</title><authors>L. Keek, J.J.M. in 't Zand</authors><categories>astro-ph</categories><comments>Contributed talk to appear in the proceedings of the &quot;7th INTEGRAL
  Workshop - An INTEGRAL View of Compact Objects&quot;, Copenhagen, Denmark, on 8-11
  September 2008</comments><journal-ref>PoS Integral08:032,2008</journal-ref><license>http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/</license><abstract>  Hydrogen and helium accreted onto a neutron star undergo thermonuclear
burning. Explosive burning is observed as a type I X-ray burst. We describe the
different burning regimes and focus on some of the current inconsistencies
between theory and observations. Of special interest are the rare kinds of
X-ray bursts such as carbon-fueled superbursts and helium-fueled intermediately
long X-ray bursts. These bursts are thought to originate deeper in the neutron
star envelope, such that they are probes of the thermal properties of the
crust. We investigate the possibility of observing superbursts with the
wide-field instruments INTEGRAL-ISGRI and Swift-BAT. We find that only the
brightest bursts are detectable.
</abstract></arXivRaw>
