<header>
 <identifier>oai:arXiv.org:0811.4637</identifier>
 <datestamp>2008-12-02</datestamp>
 <setSpec>nlin</setSpec>
 <setSpec>physics:cond-mat</setSpec>
</header>
<metadata>
 <arXivRaw xsi:schemaLocation='http://arxiv.org/OAI/arXivRaw/ http://arxiv.org/OAI/arXivRaw.xsd' xmlns='http://arxiv.org/OAI/arXivRaw/' xmlns:xsi='http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance'>
 <id>0811.4637</id><submitter>Tetsuro Konishi</submitter><version version='v1'><date>Fri, 28 Nov 2008 02:05:52 GMT</date><size>319kb</size></version><title>Apparent violation of equipartition of energy in constrained dynamical
  systems</title><authors>Tetsuro Konishi, Tatsuo Yanagita</authors><categories>cond-mat.stat-mech nlin.CD</categories><comments>4 pages, 6 figures</comments><license>http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/</license><abstract>  We propose a planar chain system, which is a simple mechanical system with a
constraint. It is composed of $N$ masses connected by $N-1$ light links. It can
be considered as a model of a chain system, e.g., a polymer, in which each bond
is replaced by a rigid link. The long time average of the kinetic energies of
the masses in this model is numerically computed. It is found that the average
kinetic energies of the masses are different and masses near the ends of the
chain have large energies. We explain that this result is not in contradiction
with the principle of equipartition. The apparent violation of equipartition is
observed not only in the planar chain systems but also in other constrained
systems. We derive an approximate expression for the average kinetic energy,
which is in qualitative agreement with the numerical results.
</abstract></arXivRaw>
